The senate takes him at his word, and is stimulated during this period into a temporary display ol activity, revising recent acts os Claudius ³, showing inclination to increase the patron’s power over his freedmen ⁴, strengthening the master's terrible hold on the fidelity of his slaves ⁵, circumscribing the limita of magisterial authority‘, and passing various other legislative decrees‚ some ol which survived in the age os the jurists'.

Also its functions as a court ol justice are called prominently into play, not only in flagrant cases ol ordinary crime ⁸, but especially to check the corruption which the spirit ol' the last rule had made prevalent. Cossutianus Capito and Numitor, ‘the pirates of the Cilicians, are struck down by a righteous thunderbolt'⁹; a similar fate overtakea Laenas, the governor of Sardinia ¹⁰, and other similar criminals ¹¹3 and the pent-up feeling against the odious accusers who had been tools lor the destruction ol the victims of Claudius and Messalina finds its outlet in the condemnation of Suillius ¹². Yet, that the course of justice certainly did not err on the side of severity was shown, not only by the mitigation ol penalty in the last-named case ¹⁸, but also by several acqulttals; in some ol which the still continuing influence ol corruption is clearly indicated ¹⁴.
